docs.abstract: Investors have reason to be dissatisfied. The trouble is that IBM has already exhausted the typical activist playbook.
docs.snippet: Investors have reason to be dissatisfied. The trouble is that IBM has already exhausted the typical activist playbook.
docs.lead_paragraph: Requests from some big shareholders for activism at IBM are likely to go nowhere. There’s no question that the company’s investors have reason to be dissatisfied. Big Blue’s top line has shrunk for 11 consecutive quarters, shares have fallen about 25 percent from their high, and there’s no hint that the company has discovered a way to reverse course. The snag is that activists don’t have an obvious playbook for IBM’s recovery either.

headline.main: Call for Activism at IBM Is Likely to Go Unheard

docs.abstract: Revenue fell 12 percent, to $19.6 billion in the latest quarter. The company says it will pursues new sources of growth, as some of its traditional hardware, software and services businesses erode.

docs.lead_paragraph: SALESFORCE SAID TO BE PREPARING FOR TAKEOVER OFFERS  | Who wants to buy Salesforce.com? That was the big question Wednesday following a report by Bloomberg News that the cloud software giant had hired financial advisers to field takeover inquiries after it was approached by a potential buyer. Unidentified people with knowledge of the matter told Bloomberg News that it was not certain that any deal would be struck, and they didn’t name any possible buyers.

headline.main: Morning Agenda: Salesforce Said to be Preparing for Takeover Offers
